How Are You Going to Die?

Andrew Zilnicki

2023-11-10

Introduction

When thinking about death, do you ever wonder about what people actually die from?
What are the causes that end lives?
Is there certain illnesses that affect more people?
Does which state you live in make a difference in how your life ends?

Questions

Domain Question

What are the top causes of deaths by number and by state?

Other Questions

  1. Does using the Age-adjusted death rate show different information about deaths per state?
  2. Does using the Age-adjusted death rate show different information about deaths per cause?
  3. Does using the per-capita death rate show different information about deaths per state?
  4. In which states is cancer most deadly using the per-capita death rate?
  5. Which states have the highest rates of suicide using the per-capita death rate?

Data Key Terms:

Year: Year of death.
X113 Cause Name: Detailed name for cause of death.
Cause Name: Short name for cause of death.
State: State where death occurred.
Deaths: Total deaths for that death and cause in a particular year.
Age adjusted Death Rate: Formula determined by total expected number of deaths divided by the sum of the standard population and the resulting quotient is multiplied by 1,000,000. This is the death rate that would have existed if the population under study had the same age distribution as the “standard” population. This is useful for summary measures adjusted for differences in age distributions.

Data Analysis

To start analyzing data we group our data by state name and cause of death. We can then plot the data of total deaths by each cause. To make it easier to view we organize the causes from descending order.

Now filter our data by total deaths for each state ordering from the least deaths to the most deathd for easy viewing.

Now let’s filter it down to the top 5 causes and the top 10 states.

This shows that California has far more deaths than even the second closest state of Florida. California has triple the number of deaths from the top 5 causes once you look at North Carolina or New Jersey.

A better way to look at causes?

It might look like some states have far more deaths from illness, but these states also have the largest populations.
What if we used the Age-adjusted data?
Would we get different results for states and causes?
